{{Infobox company | name = Perceptive Pixel, Inc. | logo = | caption = | type = [[Division (business)|Division]] of [[Microsoft]] | traded_as = | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = {{Start date|2006}} | founder = | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location = [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] | locations = 2 offices (2014) | area_served = | key_people = [[Jefferson Han]] {{small|(founder, general manager)}} | industry = Large-scale [[multi-touch]] display technology, [[education]], [[broadcast]], [[meetings]] and [[collaboration]] | products = | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = [[Microsoft]] | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = <!-- {{URL|perceptivepixel.com}} --> | footnotes = | intl = }} '''Perceptive Pixel''' is a division of [[Microsoft]] specializing in research, development and production of [[multi-touch]] [[user interface|interfaces]]. Its technology is used in fields including [[Television broadcasting|broadcast]], [[military defence|defense]], [[Geographic information system|geo-intelligence]], [[Renewable energy commercialization|energy exploration]], [[industrial design]] and [[medical imaging]].
The division originated as an independent company with the name '''Perceptive Pixel, Inc.''', headquartered in [[New York City]] and maintaining offices in [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], and [[Washington, D.C.]] Prior to the company's establishment, founder [[Jeff Han]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/112/open_features-canttouchthis.html|title=Can't Touch This|date=February 1, 2007|work= Fast Company}}</ref> publicly demonstrated multi-touch hardware and software technology at a [[TED (conference)|TED]] conference in February 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ted.com/talks/jeff_han_demos_his_breakthrough_touchscreen.html|title=Jeff Han demos his breakthrough touchscreen|date=August 1, 2006|work= TED}}</ref> Subsequently, the company shipped their first Multi-Touch Workstation and larger [[Multi-Touch Collaboration Wall]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/24/technology/24proto.html?scp=4&sq=perceptive%20pixel&st=cse|title=Prototype - Turning Point for Touch Screens|date=August 23, 2008|work= New Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-11386_3-10082642-76.html|title=Election a win for multitouch inventor|date=November 5, 2008|work= CNET News}}</ref> The latter gained widespread recognition for transforming the way [[CNN]] covered the [[2008 United States Presidental Election|2008 US Presidential elections]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2008-11-04/tech/magic.wall_1_multi-touch-technology-perceptive-pixel-cnns?_s=PM:TECH|title=The inventor behind CNN's election 'Magic Wall'|date=November 5, 2008|work=CNN|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930100929/http://articles.cnn.com/2008-11-04/tech/magic.wall_1_multi-touch-technology-perceptive-pixel-cnns?_s=PM:TECH|archivedate=September 30, 2012|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://broadcastengineering.com/newsrooms/cnn_clarifies_complex_caucus/|title=CNN clarifies complex caucus cavalcade with new 'Magic Wall'|date=January 4, 2008|work=CNN|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221014655/http://broadcastengineering.com/newsrooms/cnn_clarifies_complex_caucus/|archivedate=February 21, 2008|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/22/arts/television/22king.html?scp=1&sq=perceptive%20pixel&st=cse|title=John King of CNN Revels in His High-Tech Election Night Toy |date=April 22, 2008|work= New York Times}}</ref> In 2009, the [[Smithsonian]] awarded Perceptive Pixel the [[National Design Award]] in the inaugural category of [[Interaction Design]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationaldesignawards.org/2009/category/Interaction-Design/|title=Interaction Design - National Design Awards 2009|work= National Design Awards}}</ref>
On July 9, 2012, Microsoft CEO [[Steve Ballmer]] announced that they would [[List of mergers and acquisitions by Microsoft|acquire]] Perceptive Pixel Inc. in a transaction that closed three weeks later on July 31.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insideris.com/breaking-microsoft-buys-perceptive-pixel/|title=Breaking: Microsoft Buys Perceptive Pixel}}</ref> At that year's [[Microsoft Worldwide Partner Conference|WPC conference]], Ballmer stated the company hoped to use its newly acquired technology to enhance its [[Windows 8]] operating system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-19062196|title=Microsoft buys large-screen maker Perceptive Pixel}}</ref>
On January 21, 2015, Microsoft announced the [[Surface Hub]], a next-generation device under the [[Microsoft Surface|Surface]] brand, developed by members of the Perceptive Pixel team.<ref>{{citenews|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/21/7867585/microsoft-surface-hub-announced|title = Microsoft announces 84-inch Surface Hub tailored for Windows 10}}</ref>
